Prove or disprove: Orthogonal Transformation implies in orthogonal vector basis.

Let two vector basis be: $\mathbf e_i$ and $\mathbf f_i$. They both relate to each other by the following transformation:
$$
\mathbf f_i = \sum_j a_{ij}\mathbf e_j
$$

That is, a linear relation. It is quite trivial to prove:
$$
\left\{ 
  \begin{array}{l l}
    \mathbf e_i\cdot\mathbf e_j = \delta_{ij} & \\
    \mathbf f_i\cdot\mathbf f_j = \delta_{ij} & 
\end{array} \right.
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\sum_k a_{ik}a_{jk} = \delta_{ij}\quad\quad\mbox{ or }\quad\quad
aa^T = I
$$

Where $I$ is the identity matrix and in components $(I)_{ij} = \delta_{ij}$. Which means, $a$ has to be an orthogonal matrix. Is there a way to prove/disprove otherwise? That is, prove/disprove:
$$
\sum_k a_{ik}a_{jk} = \delta_{ij}\quad\quad\mbox{ or }\quad\quad
aa^T = I
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\left\{ 
  \begin{array}{l l}
    \mathbf e_i\cdot\mathbf e_j = \delta_{ij} & \\
    \mathbf f_i\cdot\mathbf f_j = \delta_{ij} & 
\end{array} \right.
$$

